%I A394476 #60 Jul 14 2026 19:57:46
%S A394476 3,7,29,59,467,2803,7559,65267,453107,5743499,43498187,139712759,
%T A394476 279425519
%N A394476 a(n) is the smallest integer k such that the iterated multiplicative-order chain k, ord_k(3), ord_{ord_k(3)}(3), and so on, reaches a multiple of 3 in exactly n steps.
%C A394476 The chain is defined by iterating: given an integer q with gcd(q, 3) = 1, calculate ord_q(3) (the multiplicative order of 3 modulo q), then repeat. The chain ends when a multiple of 3 is reached.
%C A394476 If the chain reaches 1, it does not end at a multiple of 3, and those integers are not included in this sequence. See crossref for the accompanying sequence of integers whose chain ends in 1.
%C A394476 A cycle in the chain is not possible.
%C A394476 Based on observations, every term for n >= 1 seems to be prime.
%C A394476 This sequence is the base-3 version of A396944.
%e A394476 a(0) = 3 because 3 is already a multiple of 3, so it takes 0 steps.
%e A394476 a(1) = 7 because the chain is 7, 6, reaching a multiple of 3 in 1 step.
%e A394476 a(2) = 29 because the chain is 29, 28, 6, reaching a multiple of 3 in 2 steps.
%e A394476 a(3) = 59 because the chain is 59, 29, 28, 6, reaching a multiple of 3 in 3 steps.
%e A394476 a(4) = 467 because the chain is 467, 233, 232, 28, 6, reaching a multiple of 3 in 4 steps.
%e A394476 a(5) = 2803 because the chain is 2803, 934, 233, 232, 28, 6, reaching a multiple of 3 in 5 steps.
%e A394476 a(6) = 7559 because the chain is 7559, 3779, 1889, 1888, 232, 28, 6, reaching a multiple of 3 in 6 steps.
%e A394476 a(7) = 65267 because the chain is 65267, 32633, 32632, 4078, 1019, 509, 508, 126, reaching a multiple of 3 in 7 steps.
%e A394476 a(8) = 453107 because the chain is 453107, 226553, 226552, 28318, 7079, 3539, 1769, 140, 12, reaching a multiple of 3 in 8 steps.
%e A394476 a(9) = 5743499 because the chain is 5743499, 2871749, 2871748, 326330, 32632, 4078, 1019, 509, 508, 126, reaching a multiple of 3 in 9 steps.
%e A394476 k = 11 is not included because the chain 11, 5, 4, 2, 1 ends at 1, not at a multiple of 3.
%o A394476 (Python)
%o A394476 from sympy import n_order
%o A394476 from math import gcd
%o A394476 def steps(k):
%o A394476     q, s = k, 0
%o A394476     while q % 3 != 0:
%o A394476         if q == 1 or gcd(3, q) != 1:
%o A394476             return -1
%o A394476         q = n_order(3, q)
%o A394476         s += 1
%o A394476     return s
%o A394476 def a(n):
%o A394476     k = 2
%o A394476     while steps(k) != n:
%o A394476         k += 1
%o A394476     return k
%o A394476 print([a(n) for n in range(0, 8)])
%Y A394476 Cf. A396944 (base-2 version), A002326, A005384.
%K A394476 nonn,hard,more,new
